  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Women in International Climate Policy</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Climate change is a serious threat to reduction of poverty and the achievement of the Millennium Development Goals. Its effects are felt strongest by the world&apos;s poorest and the weakest, of whom some 70% are women. Women can, however, have a significant impact on climate change. Forestation and increased use of renewable energy play a key role in mitigation. More widespread use of sustainable agricultural and water management principles could contribute greatly to climate adaptation. Food production and the provision of household water and energy are typically managed by women in developing countries. Empowering women can thus render climate action more effective. A key objective for Finland in climate talks is strengthening women&apos;s potential for mitigating climate change and adapting to it; this should be reflected in all climate change work programmes and funding arrangements.</narrative>
  </description>
